crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Felix Bilstein - yara-signator at cocacoding dot com

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a sophisticated kernel-mode rootkit designed for stealth and system manipulation. It employs XOR-based string obfuscation across multiple functions (e.g., sub_140005e1c, sub_140005408) to hide its strings and operational logic. The driver implements several core rootkit features: 1) File Hiding: It intercepts IRPs in sub_14000288c, modifying directory enumeration buffers to remove or hide specific files. 2) Process Hiding/Manipulation: In sub_140005408, it uses KeStackAttachProcess and PsLookupProcessByProcessId to access process memory and manipulate linked lists, likely to hide processes from the task manager. 3) Registry Filtering: It registers registry callbacks via CmRegisterCallback (sub_140003c60) to monitor or block access to specific keys. 4) Direct Kernel Object Manipulation (DKOM): It uses ObReferenceObjectByName to locate driver objects and manually overwrites function pointers (sub_140001000) to establish hooks. These behaviors, combined with dynamic routine resolution via MmGetSystemRoutineAddress, are characteristic of advanced persistent threats (APTs) or rootkit-based malware.
